\subsection{Computer Vision}

In most cases the room type classification returns reasonable results, as shown in Figure \ref{placegood}. 
\begin{figure} [h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{cc}
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/wz_imgs/4.png}} &
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/vision_test_imgs/p1.png}} \\
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/wz_imgs/3.png}} &
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/vision_test_imgs/p2.png}} \\
\end{tabular}
\caption[Examples of good place classifications]{Examples of good place classifications}
\label{placegood}
\end{figure}
If there is one fitting room type, like in the first two images, the probability of that type is high If there are similar room types, which can all be correct, like in image c and d, the probability is split mainly between those types.

However, there are images where the classifier struggles. In some images, like image a and b in Figure \ref{placebad}, the classifier is undecided between multiple room types and in other images, like image b in Figure \ref{placebad}, not enough is seen for a reasonable classification. If multiple areas of different room type are seen in an image, the probability distribution does not really reflect this because one area overrules the other, as can be seen in image d of Figure \ref{placebad}.
\begin{figure} [h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{cc}
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/vision_test_imgs/p4.png}} &
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/vision_test_imgs/p6.png}} \\
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/vision_test_imgs/p3.png}} &
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/vision_test_imgs/p5.png}} \\
\end{tabular}
\caption[Examples of not so good place classifications]{Examples of not so good place classifications}
\label{placebad}
\end{figure}
The place classification CNN does not seem to have much problems with the noise in the images and also the motion blur has at least no huge negative impact.

The object detection produces mixed results. Some object types are detected very well. These are larger objects, like monitor, bed of chair, but also some smaller objects like mouse or wine glass. Some object types, like spoon or knife, are only detected if seen very well and then also not reliably and rarely with high confidence. The detection of many other types also depends on the appearance of the object instance and the view angle. And some objects are seen where no such object is, like refrigerators at walls and cupboards and monitors at windows. In Figure \ref{obj} the object detections in some example images are shown. 
\begin{figure} [h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{cc}
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/vision_test_imgs/o1.png}} &
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/vision_test_imgs/o2.png}} \\
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/vision_test_imgs/o3.png}} &
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/vision_test_imgs/o4.png}} \\
\end{tabular}
\caption[Examples images with object detection]{Example images with object detections with a confidence greater 0.1}
\label{obj}
\end{figure}
Many other factors also affect the accuracy of the object detection, like the brightness and the background. The motion blur has a negative impact on the object detection, as can be seen by comparing image b from Figure \ref{obj} with Figure \ref{objblur}.
\begin{figure} [h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{c}
\subfloat[]{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/vision_test_imgs/o5.png}}
\end{tabular}
\caption[Examples images with object detection]{Example images with object detections with a confidence greater 0.1}
\label{objblur}
\end{figure}

The object detection produces mixed results, where some examples are shown in Figure \ref{roomobj}. Some objects are obviously not detected, like the cutlery on the table in image a, but also better visible objects are often not detected. Some objects are wrongly classified, as the monitor detections in image f and the blurriness caused by robot rotations also reduces the number of correctly detected objects, as can be seen when comparing image d and e. However, many objects are detected correctly, at least if the image is sharp and the objects are well lit and big enough in the image. The confidence of the detections varies, depending not only on how well the objects are seen but also on the background and other factors.

The doorway detection works very well, with no wrong detections and no passing of undetected doorways during the test runs. The only problem is the small field of view of the upward looking RGBD-camera. Therefore doorways are only detected if the robot is near the doorway and facing towards the doorway. This means that a doorway may not be detected while driving by, which 

\subsection{Navigation} \label{NavEval}

In general the navigation works fine and the robot is able to drive to the given goal pose. The global planning in the 2D map of the room works without problems. However the local planner and the robot movement cause some problems. The high payload brings the robot to its limits. On even and clean floors the robot moves fine, but on slippery or uneven floors the robot has not enough grip on the active wheels to execute the movements as planned because too much weight is on the passive wheels. Due to the robot's design, with the passive wheels being fixed in forward direction, rotational movements are more difficult to execute for the robot. Therefore the problem with slipping wheels only affects the rotational component of the movement. The result is that rotations are slower, curves are driven wider as planned and changes in the direction are delayed. This is most of the time no problem, but especially in narrow areas the local planner sometimes fails to keep enough distance between the robot and obstacles and the robot gets stuck. The robot can also get stuck if it drifts towards an obstacle during an in-place rotation, which happens if only one active wheel is slipping. The recovery behaviors are usually enough to unstuck the robot, but these take some time. This is a major factor for varying search times for the same test scenario. The local planner has in general a big impact on the search time because it is often not able to navigate the robot smoothly through narrow areas and around obstacles. 
